ays for contemporary readers to approach his work. It further places developments in Japanese poetry into a global context during the first decades of the twentieth century. In addition the book features a Foreword by the poet Geoffrey O’Brien and essays by Tanikawa Shuntaro, Yoshimasu Gozo, and Michael O’Brien.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPOETRY / General.2bisacsh  aavant garde.  abuddhism.  abuddhist poets.  abuddhists.  acontemporary poetry.  aearly 20th century.  aecologists.  aenglish translation.  aglobal context.  aglobal literature.  ajapanese literature.  ajapanese modernism.  ajapanese poetry.  ajapanese poets.  alit students.  alit studies.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary critics.  aliterary movements.  amiyazawa kenji.  amodern literature.  amodernism.  amodernist poetry.  apoems.  apoetry collection.  atranslated poetry.1 aO’Brien, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSato, Hiroaki, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024779640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093958540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939585423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520939585/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY